      "role": "user",
      "content": "The RAII approach makes sense, but we are actually under pretty strict MISRA C++ guidelines for this ECU, and our toolchain has very limited support for some of the newer STL features. We're trying to avoid dynamic allocation altogether after the startup phase to prevent fragmentation. \n\nIf I can't easily swap this to a smart pointer due to the environment constraints, what are some other ways to track down exactly which module is failing to free its memory? Is there a way to implement a lightweight \"tracker\" without the overhead of a full debugger?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If you are bound by MISRA C++ and must avoid dynamic allocation post-startup, you are fighting the nature of the problem, which is inherently dynamic allocation! A memory leak *is* a failure to manage dynamic memory. However, if you absolutely cannot use smart pointers, you must implement a very lightweight, custom tracking mechanism.\n\nThe best way to track this without a heavy debugger is to wrap your `new` and `delete[]` calls into custom, instrumented functions. You can create a custom memory allocator wrapper that keeps a simple count or logs the allocation size and location.\n\nHere is how you can build a rudimentary \"memory ledger\" that is lightweight enough for an ECU:\n\n1.  **Global Allocation Map:** Maintain a simple, fixed-size array or a linked list (if fragmentation is manageable) that tracks every active allocation. Each entry would store the pointer address and the size allocated.\n2.  **Instrumentation:** Replace every instance of `new` with your custom `MyAlloc()` and `delete[]` with `MyFree()`.\n3.  **Tracking Logic:**\n    *   `MyAlloc()`: Records the pointer and size into the global map. Returns the pointer.",
